45–":"1445–Deceased","1445–Female":"1445–Deceased","1438–Male":"1438–Deceased","1467–1519":"1467–1519","1419–1447":"1419–1447","1419–Female":"1419–Deceased","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1519":"1519","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","West Stow, Suffolk, England":"West Stow, Suffolk, England","Brampton, Suffolk, England":"Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crocket","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Crockett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crockett","meanings":["English (Staffordshire) and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for someone who affected a particular hairstyle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>croket</i> ‘ornamental curl or roll of hair’ (Old Norman French <i>croquet</i>, a diminutive of <i>croque</i> ‘curl, hook’)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":104,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":113,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Crocket was born in 1445, in Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Cocket, was 26 and her mother, Cocket, was 26. She married John Croftes. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in West Stow, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1445–":"1445–Surnud","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1438–Male":"1438–Surnud","1467–1519":"1467–1519","1419–1447":"1419–1447","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1519":"1519","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","West Stow, Suffolk, England":"West Stow, Suffolk, England","Brampton, Suffolk, England":"Brampton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1445–":"1445–Kuollut","1445–Female":"1445–Kuollut","1438–Male":"1438–Kuollut","1467–1519":"1467–1519","1419–1447":"1419–1447","1419–Female":"1419–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1519":"1519","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","West Stow, Suffolk, England":"West Stow, Suffolk, England","Brampton, Suffolk, England":"Brampton, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1445–":"1445–Décédée","1445–Female":"1445–Décédée","1438–Male":"1438–Décédé","1467–1519":"1467–1519","1419–1447":"1419–1447","1419–Female":"1419–Décédée","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1519":"1519","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","West Stow, Suffolk, England":"West Stow, Suffolk, Angleterre","Brampton, Suffolk, England":"Brampton, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Joan Crocket est née en 1445, à Brampton, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, John Cocket, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Cocket, avait 26 ans. Elle a épousé John Croftes. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée à West Stow, Suffolk, Angleterre."},"de":{"1445–":"1445–Verstorben","1445–Female":"1445–Verstorben","1438–Male":"1438–Verstorben","1467–1519":"1467–151